It turns out that South Africa’s economy didn’t experience a recession in 2017, Jacob Zuma’s last full year as the nation’s president. Revisions to the statistics agency’s gross domestic product data on Tuesday show the continent’s most-industrialised economy expanded 0.4% in the fourth quarter of 2016 and that it didn’t contract 0.3% as reported in December.  Gross domestic product climbed an annualised 3.1%  in the final three months of 2017, more than the 1.8% median of 14 economists’ estimates in a Bloomberg survey. Read: SA’s economy expands most in four years in 2017 © 2018 Bloomberg